<html>
<head>
<title>A Message From Aspen -- 1/18/95 -- PFF</title>
</head>
<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/pff/notebook.gif" LINK="#8C1717" VLINK="#545454" ALINK="#FF0000"> <ul><blockquote><a href="/pff"><img src="/pff/pffdoc.gif" align="right" border="0"></a>

<h2>Message from Aspen</h2>
<P>
by <a href="/pff/people/sfellow.html#Vlahos">Michael Vlahos</a></center>
<P>
Big Change is upon us.  In America, we have called this <I>revolution</I>.
 Today, it is also called <I>cyberspace</I>.
<P>
Two dozen doyens of big change and the new world met in Aspen
in August.  The theme on the table:  <I>Cyberspace and the American
Dream</I>.  Big Stuff:  an economic revolution, a transformation
of our way of life.  We asked them:  What does this mean for us,
the way we live together, do business, and govern?  Around the
table were some of the first surveyors of the digital landscape.
 It was familiar terrain for all;  so active talk we expected
&#150; and we wrangled and argued for two days about important
things, and about revolution. The last thing we expected to come
out of it all was a ringing, <I>solidarnosc</I> manifesto.
<P>
But something unexpected none the less remained.  A message runs
through the talk.  And it is a message, not for those in the know,
but for regular Americans, those to whom cyberspace is no more
than a breath of esoterica.  It is a message of needed fundamentals,
of things about big change that everyone should know.
<P>
We offer it in the form of the informal, of principles not for
incantation, but for reflection.  Words taken from the talk at
Aspen appear <I>&#147;like this.&#148;</I>
<P>
Here is our message.
<P>
<B><center>Cyberspace is not a medium, but a place.</B></center>
<P>
Before cyberspace, there was <I>the air waves</I>.  The old metaphor
was about how information traveled, how the ether took data packets
from one terminal to another.  And as a metaphor, the air waves
signaled a medium only, an agency that all wished to use;  a common,
and thus shared, instrumentality.
<P>
But cyberspace is a place.  We meet in the ether itself.  For
those who regularly play or do business there, it is even a temporary
habitation.  The new metaphor of a place becomes real;  even though
we are physically separate, our senses connect.  Information is
no longer data, but landscape.  At Aspen, when we reached for
words, they were concrete, world-words:  cyberspace as <I>&#147;ecosystem,&#148;
a new &#147;ecology,&#148;</I> <I>&#147;cyberspace is closer to
a datasphere or space of information.&#148;</I>  It has laid the
same claim on our imagination as a newly discovered country, a
frontier.  It is truly a new world.
<P>
We know it is a place because we think of it as a place.  We act
as though it is a place.  Groups of us meet there; we interact
there:  where <I>interact</I> is merely our new word for being
social.
<P>
Meaning we create human communities there.
<P>
Calling cyberspace a place is our fundamental first principle:
 first to change unstated habits of thought, and then the very
definitions of law.  It means that cyberspace is not a common
medium, a public good; which after the model of <I>the air waves</I>
needs government control and regulation if it is to be shared
as a commons.  Cyberspace is a realm, a sphere of permanent human
gathering and activity.  Primitive it is &#150; a digitally savage
place &#150; but it is, like the earliest American colonies, <B>in
the process of being settled</B>.  Since cyberspace is a created
place, our technology reach endows the possibility of its social
development, of its rise to civilization;  just as the evolution
of ships and the first computers &#150; sextant and astrolabe
&#150; made possible America itself.  So the first colonies in
cyberspace are like any other human experiments at living on a
distant shore.  They are experiments in society itself.
<P>
<B><center>The communities that grow there must be <br>private before they<I>
</I>are public.</B></center>
<P>
These experiments in cyberspace are pioneer communities, and they
may be the first stakeholders of a new society.  Not an alien
culture:  more like an extension of ourselves in a new, but very
different place.  And like any weak and distant settlement, the
new place seems oppressive in its harshness;  and from our far
away vantage &#150; like that of 17th century Londoners &#150;
it all seems primitive and strange.  And it is strange;  and the
unyielding strangeness of an alien world forces human social adaptation.
 People come to this new place with all the inherited social traditions
of late-industrial culture;  and it doesn&#146;t work that way
here.  Others have come in rebellion, or seeking sanctuary from
the tyranny of those traditions.  They want it all to be different.
<P>
What the cyber-colonists share is the desire to adapt, to be able
to be there, and stay there, and make it work.  That drives them;
 and that means, like so many fragile first settlements, that
they will find a way to make it work.  But that means finding
out above all what <I>does</I> work.
<P>
Culture is everywhere in us.  It teaches us how to arrange human
things, how to relate to one another.  And it urges us to make
rules that guide our thinking and our actions.  Law is only the
last form of human rule-making to appear.  Most societies rely
on custom and taboo; they save the law for community theater:
 a mix of teaching and collective observance.
<P>
Social rules &#150; custom and taboo as opposed to law &#150;
have become <I>private</I> in the modern sense:  that is, they
inhere to a community or group only, and are not officially owned
by the national society as a whole.  When social rules inhere
to the national society, they are no longer owned and exercised
by a community of <B>people</B>, but by the national <B>government</B>.
 This is the modern meaning of <I>public</I>.  Long ago, <I>public</I>
referred to the whole of a tribe, in a time when tribe and community
were the same word.  The industrial period separated public from
community.  The new nation state created a formal code of national
law that grew in to a superstructure of life:  it supplanted custom
and taboo for all groups, and replaced social rules with centralized
fiat.  Today, in everyday usage, public no longer means <I>of
the people</I>, it means that particular aspect of government
regulation of <I>everyone&#146;s</I> life.
<P>
Since cyberspace is still seen by America&#146;s centralized authority
as a public medium,  this authority seeks to regulate the new
ether as it did the air waves.  But suppose this authority affirmed
the new metaphor of cyberspace as a realm, colonized by pioneering
settlers?  Would the authority allow the new communities to create
their own rules?  Would it understand that old rules, hardened
into code and statute, might not fit the new place?<HR>

<P>
America&#146;s frontier communities grew up on their own.  The
British Crown did not interfere unduly in their <I>private</I>
life, even as this evolved into civic life, even to the level
of colonial assemblies.  And after we won our independence, young
America let communities continue to make their own rules.
<P>
<I>&#147;We are hearkening back to the old frontier.  At first
they spent an awful lot of time conquering the frontier and building
the frontier and making a society here where there was no one.
 And then they studied politics.&#148;</I>
<P>
Politics as governance should grow out of the traditions of community
rule.  But in industrial America rules have been codified on high,
and are imposed from above.  This reversal of original tradition
is suffered more or less passively by most citizens.  Those sodbusting
in cyberspace, however, are different.  They argue that regulation
for an industrial world will not work in the ether.  And they
are generally more &#145;ornery and defiant than most American
citizens.
<P>
Their message:  to colonize cyberspace,
<P>
<B><center>Custom must precede law.</center></B>
<P>
They want to build their own communities, not have them administered
by the state.  They insist that state-regulated human relations
in cyberspace will stunt, if not destroy, the growth of real society
there.
<P>
<I>&#147;This discussion is very evocative of communities in America
in the 18th century.  If you look at the communities that founded
America, many of them were fleeing a place of tyranny, and they
sought just to be unto themselves, and that was accepted originally
in America.  I think in some ways we have come full circle.&#148;</I>
<P>
Not just frontier spirit here, but a bit of <I>Allegheny Uprising</I>
too.  Cyberspace foments a rebellion against the Old Order.
<P>
<B><center>The new society is a successor society &#150; and so<br> a new
model.</B>
<P></center>
Why is this important?  This is surely the most marginal of frontier
societies.  Or is it?
<P>
What we call cyber-communities look more like encampments than
colonies.  But we tend to tie our image of community to the familial-neighborhood
icon only.  We forget that our economic intercourse is a highly
advanced network of business communities, marked by highly developed
sets of personal and group relationships.  In the US in fact,
a case can be made that the strongest personal ties that many
have are not family at all, but company and firm.  From core identity
to emotional investment, the communities of commerce define late
20th century America.
<P>
We call it The Marketplace.  And the new marketplace is moving
to the new place, cyberspace.  It is moving there because the
technologies of the ether <I>&#147;can make transaction costs
so small that we can eventually eliminate them.&#148;</I>  What
earthly market can say that?  And what market can ignore transaction
costs, when there is one that has none?
<P>
Like the ancient agora or bazaar, markets seek communities, and
communities cluster around the marketplace.  And as cyberspace
becomes a living social sphere, going to market there is not just
a response to zero transaction costs;  it is like going downtown
in the old city.  Communities actually, and increasingly, inhabit
the same space as the new marketplace.  Cyberspace begins to lose
its frontier edges, and edges into <I>Boom Town</I>.  More and
more people enter the ether and work there.  They don&#146;t just
get info dumps on their terminal;  the terminal becomes their
vehicle, their wheels into cyberspace.  So the new society gets
serious, and gets beyond the BBS, through the social network of
enterprise.
<P>
And because of business, the new society truly promises to succeed
the old.  It succeeds because it lets everything work faster,
better, and with higher confidence.  And it is open:  everything
is there to see.  Open markets have always worked on trust, and
each advance in transaction has been built on it.  Transparency
is its own enforcement.
<P>
Which means that the very nature of the cyberspace urges a ethos
of trust.  Transparency reaffirms the power of ostracism;  it
encourages virtue as no law of the land can.  What openness does
to business deadbeats, it does in a much larger sense for the
new society:  it renews the strength of custom over law, of group
rules self-defined over regulation by government authority.  And
it is fairer by far.  If <I>&#147;value is determined by the trust
that people have and can be engaged directly so as to define their
own currency even,&#148;</I> then each of us has the power to
shape our own value according to our actions.
<P>
So a new ethic in the marketplace at last comes home:  and the
far shores of a new world brings us back to the Atlantic shore
of our earliest ancestors;  back to that confidence in their values
and beliefs that is their charge to us.
<P>
<B><center>It threatens the old, and the old order seeks<br> to kill or stunt
it.</B></center>
<P>
But in this promise of progress is a problem.
<P>
<I>&#147;If markets are going to get immeasurably better, it should
be possible to return to the market many things that are handed
to government.&#148;</I>
<P>
Or, cyberspace as the main threat to the Old Order.
<P>
It took the American colonies almost two centuries to become a
threat to Britain&#146;s established order.  And it took long
war and a financial crisis to disrupt a century-long pattern of
British benign neglect of rule.
<P>
No such hope exists for cyberspace.  To the Old Order, the threat
of cyberspace is like the Industrial and the French revolutions
rolled into one.
<P>
<I>&#147;The fact that a system is chaotic and not capable of
control by old institutions, does not necessarily mean that it
is going to blow up like a bomb.&#148;</I>
<P>
Ah, but that is exactly how imperial Washington sees cyberspace.
 In its eyes it resembles a bomb in every respect:  it ticks like
a bomb, it is fused to blow in a finite period of time, and its
explosive power is enough to bring down the old house.
<P>
And the pioneers know it:
<P>
<I>&#147;When we start using phrases like </I>Government as the
Engine of Progress<I>, then we are deep into machine think and
machine language.&#148; ... &#147;The old machine model came out
with a perfect Hoover blueprint for everything.  Everything has
to be under control. Everything has to be in balance.  All the
pieces have to fit together.  But the machine can&#146;t evolve
or change.  And I think what we are engaged in now is the disassembly
of that super bureaucratic apparatus.&#148;</I>
<P>
or,
<P>
<I>&#147;We should be examining very critically just which freedoms
really need government to be protected&#148; ... &#147;Before
we hand back to government or say to government, oh yes, you get
to protect all our freedoms, we should ask critically just which
ones we can protect for ourselves ...&#148;</I>
<P>
All we have to do is listen to our own words.
<P>
So &#147;telecom&#148; legislation brought forward by the <I>ancien
regime</I> is offered as public reform or public protection, but
it is intended to freeze evolution.  It would be like Charles
II forbidding all ship departures from Bristol to British North
America.  Of course, that would have been a form of royal self-mutilation.
 It was beyond the 17th century imagination.
<P>
But not beyond of the mind of the late 20th century imperial bureaucrat:
<P>
<I>&#147;We are in a world with ever-increasing regulatory tentacles
reaching throughout the system, and even now beginning to invade
the information economy itself and strangle it  ...&#148;</I>
<P>
or,
<P>
<I>&#147;What we need is for telephone companies with their tremendous
fiber capacity to link to the broad band connections to homes
that cable companies now possess to create a broad band infrastructure
for the Internet.  But because regulators prohibit this natural
evolution ... capital is fleeing from the Internet ... to Hollywood.&#148;</I>
<P>
The irony is that forcing new world builders to compete over &#147;content&#148;
drives telecom back to the social universe of couch potato-TV;
 back to the stupefying, one-way feed box of industrial information
... back to the vision of George Orwell.
<P>
Back to the cultural compass of the 1950s?  Back to the future?
<P>
<B><center>We need to protect the new from the old, <br>while it is still
vulnerable.</center></B>
<P>
No regime has ever stopped relentless change.  Revolutions happen;
 the Soviet <I>nomenclatura</I> had not enough T-72s to stop theirs,
and our Imperial City has not enough Clipper Chips or Senators
Exxon to starve out the brash settlements on the Net.  But they
can slow it down, divert its course for awhile, give us all grief.
<P>
But what we have made in cyberspace is revolution&#146;s start.
 We don&#146;t have to worry about what it will do:  we know full
well what it will do.  What we must do is fight like hell to give
this juggernaut &#150; just like yesterday&#146;s locomotive of
progress &#150; its History-breaking head of steam.
<P>
<I>&#147;I am convinced that federal level government is an industrial
era artifact that arose to protect the interests of large industrial
institutions and will go away with them.&#148;</I>
<P>
<i>Michael Vlahos is a senior fellow at The Progress &amp; Freedom
Foundation. He moderated &quot;Aspen Summit '95:  Cyberspace and
the American Dream II&quot;, a conference held in Aspen, Colo.
on August 21-22, 1995, from which this report is drawn. </i> 

</blockquote></ul><p><br><center><a href="/pff/footer.map"><img src="/pff/footer.gif" border="0" ISMAP></a></center>
</body>
</HTML>

